00:26:16,340 --> 00:26:20,340
He made a number of predictions as to what the important conditions were.

457
00:26:20,340 --> 00:26:24,340
And the key ones really is that they should be very rich in hydrogen gas,

458
00:26:24,340 --> 00:26:26,340
which is true.

459
00:26:26,340 --> 00:26:30,340
And that there should be the walls of the ancient vents,

460
00:26:30,340 --> 00:26:32,340
not the modern ones, but the ancient ones should have contained

461
00:26:32,340 --> 00:26:35,340
catalytic iron sulfur minerals.

462
00:26:35,340 --> 00:26:37,340
That also seems to be true.

463
00:26:37,340 --> 00:26:39,340
But the main point that he was talking about

464
00:26:39,340 --> 00:26:41,340
is there were natural proton gradients.

465
00:26:41,340 --> 00:26:45,340
Because you have alkaline fluids, which really don't have many protons.

466
00:26:45,340 --> 00:26:47,340
They're deficient in protons.

467
00:26:47,340 --> 00:26:49,340
And a relatively acidic early ocean.

468
00:26:49,340 --> 00:26:52,340
Lots of carbon dioxide, full of protons.

469
00:26:52,340 --> 00:26:56,340
And so the two were mingling inside these vents.

470
00:26:56,340 --> 00:27:01,340
And you would have very steep proton gradients within the vents.

471
00:27:01,340 --> 00:27:03,340
We don't really know how steep.

472
00:27:03,340 --> 00:27:06,340
We don't know a great deal about these vents.

473
00:27:06,340 --> 00:27:10,340
But you can at least imagine how it might work.

474
00:27:10,340 --> 00:27:15,340
Essentially what the methanogens are doing and how, in essence,

475
00:27:16,340 --> 00:27:22,340
the proton concentration changes the reactivity of both hydrogen and CO2.

476
00:27:22,340 --> 00:27:26,340
In alkaline fluids, hydrogen is more reactive.

477
00:27:26,340 --> 00:27:29,340
It wants to offload its electrons onto something else.

478
00:27:29,340 --> 00:27:34,340
And in acidic conditions, CO2 is more reactive.

479
00:27:34,340 --> 00:27:37,340
It's going to accept the electrons because it can accept protons

480
00:27:37,340 --> 00:27:39,340
to balance the charges as well.

481
00:27:39,340 --> 00:27:43,340
And so if you've got two channels next to each other,

482
00:27:43,340 --> 00:27:46,340
the CO2 in acid conditions is going to be more receptive

483
00:27:46,340 --> 00:27:51,340
to picking up electrons and protons and becoming an organic molecule.

484
00:27:51,340 --> 00:27:54,340
And if you have hydrogen in an alkaline channel,

485
00:27:54,340 --> 00:27:57,340
it really wants to be rid of its electrons.

486
00:27:57,340 --> 00:28:01,340
And the protons will react with the hydroxide ions to make water,

487
00:28:01,340 --> 00:28:04,340
which is thermodynamically very favoured.

488
00:28:04,340 --> 00:28:08,340
But if they mix, then, of course, you've lost that.

489
00:28:08,340 --> 00:28:11,340
You've lost the structure. You've lost the barrier.

490
00:28:11,340 --> 00:28:13,340
You don't have a pH difference anymore.

491
00:28:13,340 --> 00:28:16,340
And so you've lost everything. It's the structure that really matters.

492
00:28:16,340 --> 00:28:18,340
And it's the structure that we have here.

493
00:28:18,340 --> 00:28:22,340
And these minerals that we think you would have found in these ancient vents

494
00:28:22,340 --> 00:28:26,340
in which you find today in methanogens are the ion-sulfur minerals.

495
00:28:26,340 --> 00:28:28,340
And they're semiconducting.

496
00:28:28,340 --> 00:28:30,340
So you could imagine, at least,

497
00:28:30,340 --> 00:28:33,340
that the hydrogen would pass electrons onto this barrier

498
00:28:33,340 --> 00:28:35,340
and across the barrier onto CO2.

499
00:28:35,340 --> 00:28:37,340
And that it's equivalent to a cell membrane,

500
00:28:37,340 --> 00:28:39,340
and it's the same structure as a cell membrane,

501
00:28:39,340 --> 00:28:41,340
and this is how methanogens might do it.

502
00:28:41,340 --> 00:28:45,340
Well, you could call that a wild bit of imagination,

503
00:28:45,340 --> 00:28:47,340
or you could call it a hypothesis.

504
00:28:47,340 --> 00:28:50,340
A hypothesis, I think Peter Meddewa said,

